abstract: The mayor of South Bend, Ind., has some local black leaders vouching for him. But that hasn’t stopped his opponents from criticizing his record.
snippet: The mayor of South Bend, Ind., has some local black leaders vouching for him. But that hasn’t stopped his opponents from criticizing his record.
lead_paragraph: SOUTH BEND, Ind. — Pete Buttigieg is rarely home these days as he scoots from South Carolina to New Hampshire to Iowa in pursuit of primary voters.

abstract: Rudy Giuliani didn’t get the job he expected. But as unpaid personal counsel to the president and for-profit peddler of access and advice, he got the spotlight.
snippet: Rudy Giuliani didn’t get the job he expected. But as unpaid personal counsel to the president and for-profit peddler of access and advice, he got the spotlight.
lead_paragraph: Not so long ago, it seemed to Rudolph W. Giuliani that he would be presiding over a hefty part of the world.

abstract: The lessons from Nixon and Clinton.
snippet: The lessons from Nixon and Clinton.
lead_paragraph: During Watergate, the House Judiciary Committee considered five articles of impeachment against Richard Nixon — and voted down two of them. During the impeachment of Bill Clinton, the House voted on four articles — and rejected two.

headline_main: The Eight Counts of Impeachment That Trump Deserves

abstract: The best course for the House is to present a case for impeachment focused on Ukraine and the danger to the 2020 elections.
snippet: The best course for the House is to present a case for impeachment focused on Ukraine and the danger to the 2020 elections.
lead_paragraph: President Trump has now made obvious his contempt for the notion that Congress has any authority to hold him accountable. He has signaled that he won’t mount any defense to impeachment charges in the House over his scheming in Ukraine, insisting it is somehow beneath him to participate in a constitutional process.

headline_main: Does Trump Think Our Constitutional Processes Are Beneath Him?

abstract: President Trump is refusing to engage and Democrats have concluded they will press ahead anyway, rendering a historic undertaking little more than a foregone conclusion.
snippet: President Trump is refusing to engage and Democrats have concluded they will press ahead anyway, rendering a historic undertaking little more than a foregone conclusion.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Almost from the moment that Speaker Nancy Pelosi and her lieutenants decided this fall to pursue the impeachment of President Trump, they made a fateful judgment: If the president intended to do nothing but stonewall and subvert their inquiry, they were not going to be the ones politely sticking to lofty traditions.

headline_main: With White House Absent, Impeachment Devolves Into Partisan Brawl
headline_print_headline: White House Defiance Turns Impeachment Into a Partisan Brawl
byline_original: By Michael D. Shear, Nicholas Fandos and Maggie Haberman

abstract: Before issuing his own condolences, the president channeled the Saudi king’s, and avoided any discussion of the hard questions about why the U.S. is training Saudi officers.
snippet: Before issuing his own condolences, the president channeled the Saudi king’s, and avoided any discussion of the hard questions about why the U.S. is training Saudi officers.
lead_paragraph: FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. — When a Saudi Air Force officer opened fire on his classmates at a naval base in Pensacola, Fla., on Friday, he killed three, wounded eight and exposed anew the strange dynamic between President Trump and the Saudi leadership: The president’s first instinct was to tamp down any suggestion that the Saudi government needed to be held to account.

abstract: How Bernie and Biden both channel the current distrust of technocrats.
snippet: How Bernie and Biden both channel the current distrust of technocrats.
lead_paragraph: In last Sunday’s column, I argued that Democrats looking for someone to unify their fractious coalition should take another glance at Bernie Sanders — on the grounds that he’s more popular across the party’s different factions, more unifying, more exciting and more potentially appealing to non-liberals than his critics tend to assume.
